language Essence 1.3

$ Social Golfers Problem — Formulation 4: Matrix of Partitions
$
$ Domain:  matrix indexed by [int(1..w)] of partition (regular, numParts g, partSize s) from Golfers
$
$ Information carried by the domain:
$   - Fixed array of w partitions, one per week
$   - Each partition has g groups of size s (regular)
$   - Disjointness and coverage: partition semantics
$
$ Explicit constraints needed:
$   - Pairing constraint
$
$ Compared to Formulations 1–3:
$   - Functionally similar to the function and sequence formulations
$     (indexed access to partitions).
$   - The matrix is the most common Essence container for indexed collections.
$   - No additional constraints beyond pairing are needed, since the partition
$     domain still encodes all within-week structure.

given w, g, s : int(1..)

letting nGolfers be g * s
letting Golfers be new type of size nGolfers

find sched : matrix indexed by [int(1..w)] of partition (regular, numParts g, partSize s) from Golfers

$ Pairing constraint
such that
    forAll p1 : Golfers .
        forAll p2 : Golfers .
            p1 != p2 ->
            (sum i : int(1..w) .
                sum part in parts(sched[i]) .
                    toInt(p1 in part /\ p2 in part)
            ) <= 1
